Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for Next.js

## Changes Implemented:

### 1. Installed Dependencies
- Added `@vercel/analytics` package to the project using npm
- Package version installed: Latest stable version via npm install

### 2. Modified Files

**app/layout.tsx**
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next"`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after `{children}`
- Preserved existing code structure and formatting
- The Analytics component is now included in the root layout, which means it will be active on all pages

**package.json**
- Added `@vercel/analytics` to the dependencies section

**package-lock.json**
- Updated lock file to include @vercel/analytics and its dependencies (710 packages added)

## Implementation Details:

This is an App Router project (Next.js with `app` directory), so the Analytics component was added to the root layout file (`app/layout.tsx`) as recommended by Vercel's documentation.

The Analytics component was placed inside the `<body>` tag after the `{children}` component, which is the recommended placement for optimal performance and functionality.

## Verification:

✓ Build completed successfully (`npm run build`)
✓ Linter passed with no errors (`npm run lint`)
✓ TypeScript compilation successful
✓ All dependencies properly installed and lock file updated

## Next Steps:

The Vercel Web Analytics is now configured and will automatically start collecting anonymous analytics data when the application is deployed to Vercel. No additional configuration is required for basic functionality.

If you need to enable advanced features like custom events or Audiences, you can refer to the Vercel Analytics documentation: https://vercel.com/docs/analytics
